## What This Is

The **Open Maintenance Framework (OMF)** is a structured operational architecture that translates governance decisions and treasury capital into sustained, accountable maintenance programs for open source infrastructure.

OMF addresses the gap that every existing OSS funding initiative leaves open: **funding mechanisms exist, but operational architectures do not.** Treasuries can authorize payments. Governance bodies can vote. What is missing is the layer that connects those decisions to the ongoing work of infrastructure maintenance — the programs, processes, accountability structures, and portfolio discipline required to sustain critical open source over time.

OMF is:
- **Portable** — governance-agnostic, blockchain-agnostic, organizationally neutral
- **Modular** — each program can be implemented independently; no prerequisites
- **Stewardship-oriented** — built for infrastructure maintenance, not feature development
- **Portfolio-driven** — allocates funding by dependency risk, not by proposal quality

OMF is not:
- A governance system or DAO
- A foundation or legal entity
- A funding source
- A replacement for on-chain governance
- Dependent on a dOSPO or any other framework

> The sustainability crisis in open source is not primarily a funding problem. It is an operational layer problem. Funding exists, or can be created. What is missing is the architecture that translates resources into outcomes.

