## When To Use This

**✅ OMF is appropriate when:**

- Your ecosystem has treasury capital but critical infrastructure remains under-maintained
- Funding decisions are made proposal-by-proposal with no portfolio-level visibility
- Grants and bounties are your primary maintenance funding mechanisms — and maintainers are burning out
- You have no structured contributor pipeline to grow the next generation of maintainers
- Security incidents reveal that no standing coordination mechanism exists
- You want to move from ad hoc coordination to accountable, evidence-based programs

**❌ OMF is not appropriate when:**

- The ecosystem is too early-stage for formal operational programs
- Dependency failures are localized and recoverable
- Coordination overhead would exceed failure cost
- You haven't conducted a dependency audit — start there first

**The minimum readiness test:** Does your ecosystem have at least one piece of critical infrastructure maintained by a single individual with no formal support, succession plan, or compensation? If yes, OMF applies.

