## The Four Legitimacy Safeguards

OMF achieves legitimacy without centralized authority through four structural safeguards — not cultural norms.

| Safeguard | What It Means |
|---|---|
| **Governance Authorization** | All programs operate within parameters authorized by ecosystem governance. Operators execute; they do not set priorities independently. |
| **Operator Replaceability** | No single operator, organization, or individual becomes an irreplaceable dependency. An operator that cannot be replaced has captured its program. |
| **Maintainer Autonomy** | Financial or operational support does not grant operators authority over project roadmaps, technical direction, or governance structures. |
| **Public Transparency** | All program activities, funding allocations, and ecosystem health metrics remain publicly visible. Transparency enables decentralized oversight. |

Together these safeguards allow OMF to function as **neutral infrastructure stewardship** rather than institutional control.

→ Full specification: [`LEGITIMACY-SAFEGUARDS.md`](LEGITIMACY-SAFEGUARDS.md)

